Samasilin breathed out a flame, igniting a small patch of forest. He then circled above it, observing the opportunity. Curiously, as he slowed down, the strange high-pitched screams behind him also ceased. Samasilin forgot that there was still a passenger on his back.
"Please, Tenuk, you weren't unable to transform into a Slacx before!"
"Flying on your own and being suddenly dragged away by a huge pink dragon are two different things!"
"Alright, Kayer?"
Kayer clearly disagreed with Nixie's statement. He looked paler than usual, and his claws were deeply embedded in Sazarin's back, drawing blood from the Strakks. However, Sazarin didn't seem to mind. Although he realized that he had frightened his new friend, Sazarin found an open area to land.
"Sorry sorry, I smelled something. I have to deal with it!"
"Do you have to drag us along too?" Tenuk climbed off SasaLin's back, sliding down the tail to the ground, and asked with a sharp tone. "We left Revtvik! We abandoned that strong and combative big guy! How will he find us?!"
"He'll figure it out..." Nixie clicked her tongue. "Revtvik is slow, but not dumb."
"Can Revtvik drive?"
Nixie blinked, turning her head to look at Tenuk. "Of course Revtvik can drive."
"Have you ever seen Revtvik drive? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kayler. He started riding in cars to work because you always drove us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. SasaLin suddenly burst into uncontrollable laughter, but no one knew why. It took SasaLin a while to calm down.
"Sorry sorry, I just imagined my big armored friend riding a bicycle designed for Themsen children. That image is so hilarious! I wish I could read minds. This idea is too amusing! I must treasure it!"
Kayler laughed as well because he could imagine what SasaLin was thinking. "Okay, okay. But what did you smell? Why did you fly so fast?"
SasaLin grunted, took off, and disappeared quickly. Then he came back, leaving a dead Orozarak—such a rare golden-white dragon species—before Nixie. Its head was gone. "Another one is dead. I heard their cries. I smelled their blood. I must protect them and hunt the killer. This is Isini's command. Those creatures are nearby."
The huge Slacx suddenly stiffened. Nixie and Kayler also stiffened, their attention drawn to a gap at the edge of the clearing. A large and black entity was staring at them, hissing. It spread its two pairs of giant wings and charged forward, its target straight at SasaLin, completely ignoring the three little ones blocking its path. Kayler and Tenuk barely managed to dodge to the side, but Nixie found herself thrown to the ground, almost being flung onto SasaLin.
SasaLin grabbed Nixie and used its long and agile tail to toss her onto its back, then took off into the air. The black creature with two pairs of wings rapidly chased after them.
Kayler made a disapproving noise, drew his rifle from behind, opened the bag, and took out a bullet belt. He hung the belt around his chest for easy access, but soon realized that Nixie, SasaLin, and the monster had all vanished without a trace.
"Hey, Tenuk, can you transform into a flying creature?" Kayler asked.
"Do you want to give chase?"
“Bullshit.”
“But… one of them is a giant monster!”
“So what? I have a powerful rifle here. I can shoot at it anytime. All I need to do is see it to bring it down.”
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then stepped back to give himself some space. With a low and slightly painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turned into scales, and his arms transformed into wings. He quickly became a regular light-blue Slacx, but his eyes remained red.
“Hop on.”
Now Tenuk looked more like an ordinary Slacx, with neatly arranged scales on his back and a pair of sharp spikes to help Kayler grab onto him. It took Tenuk a long time to take off, but once airborne, he quickly adjusted his direction and pursued them with great effort.
However, Tenuk and Kayler soon realized they were not facing just one opponent. Another dark monster emerged from below them, and Tenuk narrowly avoided a collision.
“I guess this is the other terrifying big monster Raneeks was worried about,” Kayler frowned, trying to aim at the second monster but missing, and swiftly reloaded.
Tenuk did not respond; he was busy flying towards Nixie and SasaLin, even though the other monster was chasing them. Kayler clumsily turned around to face the monster. He considered it a good sign that the monster was chasing them, making it easier to aim and shoot. Two bullets pierced through the monster’s upper wing, which let out a painful roar before disappearing into the woods. Kayler was unsure if the monster was still following them but believed it would be unable to keep up.
Ahead, SasaLin was wildly thrashing its body, spraying flames at the black monster, while Nixie desperately clung to SasaLin to avoid falling off. Although the monster was certainly injured, it seemed to be angered and unwilling to retreat, and the fireballs didn’t appear to cause significant damage. Once SasaLin steadied itself, Nixie took the opportunity to pull out her trusted shotgun. Of course, a shotgun wouldn’t work on such a monster, but perhaps the scattered bullets could scare this black beast away?
